Q1. What is Java?
Java is a high-level, object-oriented programming language used to build software applications.
It is platform-independent because it runs on JVM (Java Virtual Machine).
Java follows the principle “Write Once, Run Anywhere”.
ex:
public class Hello {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello Java");
    }
}

Q2. What are control statements?
Control statements are used to control the flow of execution in a program.
They decide which block of code should execute based on conditions or repetition.
They include decision-making, looping, and jump statements.
ex:
int marks = 75;

if (marks >= 60)
    System.out.println("Pass");
else
    System.out.println("Fail");

Q3. Difference between while and do-while loop?
The while loop checks the condition first before executing the code block.
The do-while loop executes the code at least once before checking the condition.
So, do-while guarantees one execution even if the condition is false.
ex:
int j = 10;

do {
    System.out.println(j);
} while (j < 5);

Q4. What are operators in Java?
Operators are special symbols used to perform operations on variables and values.
They are used for arithmetic, comparison, logical operations, and assignments.
They help in performing calculations and decision-making in programs.
ex:
int a = 10, b = 3;

System.out.println(a % b);
System.out.println(a > b && b > 0);

int max = (a > b) ? a : b;

Q5. What is a String?
A String is a sequence of characters used to store text in Java.
It is immutable, meaning its value cannot be changed after creation.
Any modification creates a new String object in memory.
ex:
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = s1.concat(" World");

System.out.println(s1);
System.out.println(s2);

Q6. What are String methods?
String methods are built-in functions used to manipulate text data.
They help in finding length, extracting parts, and searching text.
They make string handling easier and more efficient.
ex:
String s = "Java Programming";

System.out.println(s.length());
System.out.println(s.substring(0, 4));
System.out.println(s.indexOf("Pro"));

Q7. String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer?
String is immutable, so every modification creates a new object.
StringBuilder is mutable and faster but not thread-safe.
StringBuffer is mutable and thread-safe but slightly slower.
ex:
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hi");
sb.append(" There");

System.out.println(sb);

Q8. What are OOP concepts?
OOP is a programming style based on objects and classes.
It helps in organizing code using real-world modeling concepts.
Its four pillars are Encapsulation, Inheritance, Polymorphism, and Abstraction.
ex:
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("eats");
    }
}

Q9. What is Encapsulation?
Encapsulation means wrapping data and methods into a single unit (class).
It hides data using private variables and provides access through methods.
It improves security and prevents direct modification of data.
ex:
class Account {
    private double balance;

    void deposit(double amt) {
        balance += amt;
    }

    double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}

Q10. What is Inheritance?
Inheritance allows one class to acquire properties of another class.
It promotes code reusability and reduces redundancy.
It creates a parent-child relationship between classes.
ex:
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("eats");
    }
}
ex:
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("barks");
    }
}

Q11. What is Polymorphism?
Polymorphism means “many forms” of a method or object.
It allows the same method to behave differently in different situations.
It improves flexibility and reusability of code.
ex:
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal sound");
    }
}
ex:
class Cat extends Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Meow");
    }
}

Q12. What is Abstraction?
Abstraction hides internal implementation details and shows only essential features.
It reduces complexity by focusing on what an object does instead of how.
It is achieved using abstract classes or interfaces.
ex:
abstract class Shape {
    abstract void draw();
}

Q13. What is a Constructor?
A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects.
It is called automatically when an object is created.
It has the same name as the class and no return type.
ex:
class Student {
    String name;

    Student(String n) {
        name = n;
    }
}

Q14. this vs super keyword?
this refers to the current class object.
super refers to the parent class object.
They are used to differentiate variables and access parent properties.
ex:
class Parent {
    int x = 10;
}
ex:
class Child extends Parent {
    int x = 20;

    void show() {
        System.out.println(this.x);
        System.out.println(super.x);
    }
}

Multithreading
Q15. What is Multithreading?
Multithreading allows multiple tasks to run at the same time.
Each thread runs independently but shares the same memory.
It improves performance and CPU utilization.
ex:
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running");
    }
}

Q16. What is Synchronization?
Synchronization is used to control access to shared resources.
It ensures that only one thread accesses a resource at a time.
It prevents data inconsistency and race conditions.
ex:
class Counter {
    int count = 0;

    synchronized void increment() {
        count++;
    }
}

Arrays
Q17. What is an Array?
An array is a data structure that stores multiple values of the same type.
It uses index-based access starting from 0.
It has fixed size and provides fast access to elements.
ex:
int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};

System.out.println(arr[1]);

DSA SECTION
Q18. What is an Array in DSA?
Array is a linear data structure with contiguous memory allocation.
It provides constant time access using index.
Insertion and deletion are costly due to shifting of elements.

Q19. What is Linked List?
A Linked List is a linear data structure made of nodes.
Each node contains data and a reference to the next node.
It allows dynamic memory allocation and easy insertion/deletion.
ex:
class Node {
    int data;
    Node next;
}

Q20. What is Stack?
Stack follows LIFO (Last In First Out) principle.
Insertion and deletion happen only from one end called top.
It is used in recursion, undo operations, and expression evaluation.
ex:
Stack<Integer> st = new Stack<>();
st.push(10);
st.pop();

Q21. What is Queue?
Queue follows FIFO (First In First Out) principle.
Insertion happens at rear and deletion at front.
It is used in scheduling and BFS traversal.
ex:
Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
q.add(10);
q.poll();

Q22. What is a Tree?
A tree is a hierarchical data structure with nodes and edges.
It has a root node and child nodes forming levels.
It is widely used in databases and file systems.
ex:
     10
    /  \
   5    15

Q23. What is Sorting?
Sorting is arranging data in ascending or descending order.
It improves searching and data processing efficiency.
Common algorithms are Bubble, Selection, Insertion, Merge, and Quick sort.

Q24. What is Searching?
Searching is finding an element in a data structure.
Linear search checks each element one by one.
Binary search divides search space and works on sorted data.

Q25. What is an Algorithm?
An algorithm is a step-by-step procedure to solve a problem.
It must be finite, clear, and efficient.
It takes input, processes it, and produces output.
Algorithms are analyzed using time and space complexity.
They help in designing efficient solutions for problems.
